Problem Description:
You are processing a live stream of lowercase characters. As each character arrives, you must
determine the earliest character in the stream that has appeared exactly once so far. If at any
point every character received has appeared at least twice, print -1. You must implement this
efficiently using a Queue to maintain the order of arrival and a frequency tracking mechanism.

Sample Test Case 1:
Input: racecar
Output: r r r r r r e
Explanation: 'r' remains the oldest unique character through the first six letters because,
although 'a' and 'c' repeat, 'r' does not repeat until the very last character. When the final 'r'
arrives, all previous characters ('r', 'a', 'c') have repeated, leaving 'e' as the only and earliest
unique character.
Sample Test Case 2:
Input: aabbcdefgh
Output: a -1 b -1 c c c c c c
Explanation: The first two 'a's cancel each other out to output -1, then the arrival of 'b's does
the same, leaving the queue empty again. Once 'c' arrives, it becomes the oldest unique
character and remains so for the rest of the stream, as 'd' through 'h' are all "younger" than 'c'.



Solution:- 

#include<stdio.h>
#include<stdlib.h>
#include<string.h>

#define MAX 1000
int main(){
    printf("Hello World!\n");
    char S[MAX];
    printf("PLease enter the string: ");
    scanf("%s", &S);
    char queue[MAX];
    int front = 0; 
    int rear = -1;
    int freq[26] = {0};
    int n = strlen(S);
    for(int i = 0; i<n; i++){
        char ch = S[i];
        freq[ch -'a']++;
        queue[++rear] = ch;
        while(front<=rear && freq[queue[front] -'a'] >1){
            front++;
        }
        if(front<=rear){
            printf("%c", queue[front]);
        } 
        else{
            printf("-1");
        }
    }
    return 0;
}

